<br>
1. Currently we have water quality standards set at 6 parts per million. Those minimums are &quot;not&quot; being met by the Corps of Engineers. As long as that continues additional flow will allow more low oxygenated water to be cast farther down river. This issue is compounded by the fact that low oxygen tends to occur in the fall of the year. Thus it greatly effects the spawn every year. Last year the DO issues basically destroyed the spawn below Bull Shoals dam and greatly effected the spawn on the Norfork.<br>
<br>
2. Additional water will create a different river. This will mean we will be forced to change the way we fish. The fish that are in the river will hold on the current habitat. Generally the preferred holds are in the center of the river or in the deeper pools. The additional water will effect considerably our ability to sight cast to fish. For some people this may not be an issue but it would all but eliminate the way that many of us earn our living.<br>
<br>
3. Additional water would change the level of &quot;wadeable&quot; water. I guide people every day that have issue with their ability to wade in certain sections of the river. In many of the preferred holds we &quot;have&quot; to cross the river in order to fish. Limited access requires us to wade the river to get to where the fish are. Crossing to the island at Rim Shoal is tenuous already. Additional water would make it impossible for some people.<br>
<br>
These are not impossible issues to be worked around. We could add additional Catch and release areas to make up the difference to loss of our water. SWPA and COE could insure water quality standards. We as guides and fly fishers could start fishing from drift boats like many of the western fly fishers have become accustomed to. However I'd like to have some assurances that these are going to take place before I feel comfortable in placing my full support behind minimum flow. I definitely believe that AGFC is entitled to mitigated flows. They should be allocated a percentage of the available acre feet to do with as they please. <br>
<br>
In summary I am really close to supporting this program. At this point I feel as though there are a few questions still to be answered. Darrell is a very qualified biologist and my friend. I'm sure that he is looking at the big picture for the river. My concerns are selfish but fly fishing is the way I make my living and I'm &quot;worried&quot; that it will be greatly effected by minimum flow.<br>
<br>
John <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=flyfishar>FlyFishAR</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 778<br> <font color=#000000>(10/31/03 5:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.flyfishingarkansas.com/Photo%20Gallery/tn_j.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Lamprey &amp; Minumum Flow-the Biologist' Take</span><hr size=1> Additionally I note that they only saw 1.5% to 2.7% of the trout effected by the lamprey. Most lamprey that I've delt with released a fish as soon as it was hooked. I rarely get one to the net. I would imagine that would be pretty much the same thing in a shocking program. <br>
